Group detection

There are also a couple of algorithms available for detecting groups. They all share the same prefix: group_.

?group_graph

Here, I will use the Girman-Newman algorithm (group_edge_betweenness()). It removes nodes with high edge betweenness. As they lie on many paths (from different groups), removing them will make clusters more distinct, hence visible.

edgelist <- read_csv("data/jamaika/jamaika_data.csv") %>% 
  group_by(from, to, type) %>% 
  summarize(weight = sum(weight)) 
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   X1 = col_double(),
##   from = col_character(),
##   to = col_character(),
##   weight = col_double(),
##   type = col_character(),
##   date = col_double(),
##   party = col_character()
## )
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'from', 'to' (override with `.groups` argument)
nodelist <- read_csv("data/jamaika/nodes.csv") %>% 
  rename(party = partei)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   name = col_character(),
##   partei = col_character()
## )
jamaika_graph <- tbl_graph(nodelist, edgelist, directed = FALSE) %>% 
  filter(!node_is_isolated())

library(ggraph)
ggraph(jamaika_graph) +
  geom_edge_link0(aes(edge_alpha = weight), edge_color = "grey66") +
  geom_node_point(aes(fill = party), shape = 21) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("CDU" = "black",
                               "CSU" = "black",
                               "SPD" = "red",
                               "DIE GRUENEN" = "green",
                               "FDP" = "yellow",
                               "AFD" = "lightblue",
                               "DIE LINKE" = "purple",
                               "Fraktionslos" = "brown")) 
## Using `stress` as default layout

clusters <- jamaika_graph %>% 
  activate(edges) %>% 
  filter(type == "retweet") %>% 
  activate(nodes) %>% 
  filter(!node_is_isolated()) %>% 
  mutate(cluster = group_edge_betweenness(), 
         cluster = as.character(cluster),
         cluster = fct_lump(cluster))
  

ggraph(clusters) +
  geom_edge_link0(aes(edge_alpha = weight), edge_color = "grey66") +
  geom_node_point(aes(fill = as_factor(cluster)), shape = 21)
## Using `stress` as default layout

Node relations

There do also exist some measures that deal with how nodes are related: ?pair_measures

jamaika_graph %N>% 
  mutate(distance_to = node_distance_to(1)
         ) %>% 
  as_tibble()

Nodes’ neighborhood

?local_graph

  simplify() %>% 
  as_tbl_graph() %N>% 
  mutate(ave_degree = local_ave_degree()) %>%
